<HEADLINE>
<P>
PALM LATITUDES: L.A. SPEAK; POSTAL PARLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Carrie St. Michel 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 animals: n . postal employees who work outside on docks, loading and unloading 
mail trucks. 
</P>
<P>
 baby buggy: n . a large, canvas-sided cart used to transport mail between work 
stations within a post office. 
</P>
<P>
 bomb: n . when the volume of mail that must be sorted is particularly heavy. 
"Every Christmas, we get hit with a bomb. " 
</P>
<P>
 early out: n . a short shift that results from a light volume of mail. "It's 
slow today, we should get an early out. " 
</P>
<P>
 nixie: n. a piece of mail on which the city and ZIP code do not match. 
</P>
<P>
 outsides: n . oversized parcels. 
</P>
<P>
 skin the rack: v. to take mailbags for distribution to local post offices. 
"It's 1:15; let's skin the rack and get moving." 
</P>
<P>
 zombie: n . a postal worker who has been assigned to the graveyard shift. 
</P>
</TEXT>
