<P>
 I HAD A FATHER: A Post-Modern Autobiography by Clark Blaise (Addison-Wesley: 
$12.; 204 pp.) . As a child, Wesley had to endure his father's womanizing, 
shady dealings and pathological lies. He attempts to come to grips with his 
pain in these fragmented recollections of a search for identity that lead to an 
ancestral home in rural Quebec and provided insights into his own interracial 
marriage. Unfortunately, the author's moments of genuine insight get buried in 
rambling attempts to mythologize his condition. 
