<P>
 SEASONS OF THE COYOTE edited by Philip L. Harrison (Tehabi/HarperCollins West: 
$ ?? ; 114 pp., paperback original). Intelligent, adaptable and persistent, the 
coyote inhabits virtually every corner of North America, despite ill-advised 
campaigns to exterminate it. The brief essays in this attractive volume extol 
the cleverness and scroungy beauty of the coyote and recap the important place 
it occupies in Amerindian mythologies. The color pictures are striking and 
exceptionally crisp, but the decision to print the text on shaded paper makes 
the book hard to read. 
