<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE BALKAN EXPRESS: Fragments From the Other Side of War by Slavenka Drakulic 
(HarperPerennial: $11.; 165 pp.). A journalist of Croatian descent who lives in 
Zagreb, Drakulic recounts the experiences of individuals who have endured -- 
and those who have perpetrated -- the horrors racking former Yugoslavia.A young 
soldier recalls shooting someone for the first time; a student plots the 
disenfranchisement of a benefactor; an old friend becomes a refugee. Drakulic 
decries the perverse mentality that strips friends, lovers and neighbors of 
their individuality and reduces them to anonymous ethnic statistics: "The 
irrational that dwells in each of us is being unleashed from its chain and 
nobody can control it anymore . . . because the demons in us have already made 
people perceive themselves as nothing but parts of the national being. . . . If 
there is any future at all, I am afraid of the time to come." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
