<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'TIME INDEFINITE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Peter Rainer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Documentary maker Ross McElwee's follow-up to his cult hit "Sherman's March," 
follows his life in the recent past.He attends a family reunion in Charlotte, 
N.C., is married and endures a series of unforeseen sorrows. What starts out as 
jaunty and dawdling becomes a kind of meditation on mortality. But McElwee 
(pictured, with friend Charleen Swansea) doesn't make you wince at his 
seriousness. His bafflement at what is going on in his life is a genuine, 
unadorned response to tragedy. You don't feel as if he's exploiting his ill 
fortune. This is a one-of-a-kind movie because McElwee himself seems one of a 
kind (KCET Tuesday at 10 p.m.). Peter Rainer 
</P>
</TEXT>
