<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUR MORTGAGE; IS IT WISE TO BUY OR WAIT FOR RATES TO FALL? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DIAN HYMER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Should I buy now or wait for interest rates to drop? 
</P>
<P>
 As interest rates rise, some home buyers are debating whether to buy now or 
wait for rates to come down. Others are racing to buy before rates climb 
further. 
</P>
<P>
 Interest rates on fixed-rate mortgages have increased more than 1.5% during 
the past few months. As rates go up, so does the cost of a new house. Buyers 
who don't have the financial ability to pay for more expensive housing have 
several options. They can scale down their housing requirements and buy a less 
expensive house. They can switch from fixed to adjustable-rate financing, which 
makes qualifying easier. 
</P>
<P>
 Or they can drop out of the house hunt altogether and wait for housing to 
become more affordable again. Buying a less expensive house makes sense as long 
as you buy a house that will suit your needs for four to five years. Moving is 
costly. It wouldn't make sense to buy a house that you know you'll outgrow in a 
year or two, particularly if you're buying into a market where home values are 
stable or where they're declining. 
</P>
<P>
 However, if you buy into a booming market where home prices are rising 
rapidly, buying a short-term house can be an excellent investment. In this 
case, postponing a purchase could cost you more than it would to buy now and 
move again in several years. 
</P>
<P>
 Even buyers who can afford fixed-rate loans are switching to adjustable rate 
mortgages (ARMs) to save money. ARMs are still available with start rates in 
the 5% to 6% range. Buyers who are having difficulty qualifying at higher 
interest rates, should shop around for an ARM program that qualifies borrowers 
based on the starting interest rate. If the initial ARM rate is a discounted 
rate, lenders often require that you qualify at 2% above the start rate (that 
is, at 7% rather than 5%.) 
</P>
<P>
 When considering an ARM, always look at the worst case scenario. How long will 
the initial interest rate be in effect and what will the interest rate be after 
the first adjustment? How high can the interest rate go if interest rates 
continue to climb? How long will it take for the ARM rate to reach the maximum 
allowed under the loan program? 
</P>
<P>
 First-Time Tip: Buyers who intend to move again within the next five years 
will probably save money by taking an ARM because of the current cost of 
fixed-rate financing. But, make sure that you won't be charged a payment for 
early prepayment if you do plan to move again soon. 
</P>
<P>
 Buyers who can't live with the uncertainty of mortgage payments that fluctuate 
should consider one of the hybrid loan products. These loans have interest 
rates that are fixed for 3, 5, 7 or 10 years. At the end of this time, the loan 
either converts to an ARM, or to another fixed rate, or it must be paid off in 
full. The initial fixed rate on these loans is lower than the rate on a 
fixed-rate loan that's due in 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
 Another option for buyers who are nervous about the interest rate fluctuations 
is to select an ARM with a relatively stable index. Ask a mortgage broker to 
explain the different index options to you. 
</P>
<P>
 The Closing: It's risky to wait for housing to become more affordable again 
before you buy. Although no one knows for sure which way rates will go in the 
future, there's speculation that interest rate increases lie ahead. If home 
values rise while you wait for rates to come back down, you'll end up spending 
more for a house, not less. 
</P>
<P>
 Distributed by Inman News Features .  
</P>
<P>
 For a copy of Dian Hymer's brochure on "Options for Cash-Short Buyers , " send 
$3 and a self-addressed, stamped envelope to Inman News Features -- OPTIONS, 
5335 College Ave . , Suite 25, Oakland, Calif. 94618.  
</P>
</TEXT>
